Video shows illegal guns and other weapons on display at the weapon destruction event Monday in Wuhan, capital of Central China’s Hubei Province. Video: Guo Yuandan/GTOver 100,000 illegal guns including types carried by US military and police officers in active duty as well as a large number of explosives were destroyed on Monday by police in 154 Chinese cities. The weapons destruction events were held in Wuhan, capital of Central China's Hubei Province, Shenyang in Northeast China Liaoning Province, Fuzhou in Southeast China Fujian Province, Yulin in South China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Luzhou in Southwest China's Sichuan Province.The event is themed to "secure the grand celebration of the founding anniversary of the People's Republic of China this year," according to the Ministry of Public Security on Monday. Another 149 Chinese cities also participated in the Monday events, which were broadcast by major media outlets including China Central Television (CCTV). A Global Times reporter in Wuhan noticed nine of the illegal guns that were exhibited were the same type used by US police officers and the military. The illegal weapons destroyed on Monday were either confiscated or turned over to police forces across the country since last year. They include 107,000 illegal air guns and shotguns and a large amount of explosives, including dynamite and detonators.Private ownership of guns is strictly prohibited in China.Monday's event was the second of its kind. In September 2018, more than 140,000 illegal guns and explosives were destroyed in 146 cities. On Monday, police provided details of what they called the largest cross-border illegal guns trafficking and smuggling case the country has ever seen.On August 4, Wuhan customs seized three boxes containing parts of guns which smugglers were attempting to bring into China from the US. Local police arrested 11 suspects and seized 46 parts for guns of various types, including some 70 firearm accessories for US guns. In December 2018, police experts also discovered gun parts were being sold on commercial online platforms including Taobao and JD.com.Police in Zhijiang of Hubei Province discovered 1,142 transactions on those platforms and arrested 19 online vendors of illegal weapons. Police confiscated 41 complete guns, more than 1,300 bullets and 13 bullets-making machines. Following such online leads, police say they have cracked 67 cases involving illegal weapons in some 20 provinces and cities in China. As of the press time, police across the nation had busted 16,000 cases involving illegal guns and explosives, cracked down on 163 criminal gangs and 117 criminal "dens," and handled 17,000 criminal suspects.The police official data shows that the number of cases involving illegal guns and explosives in China has dropped by 20 percent year-on-year between January and July.  
